'''all-out'''
also '''all out'''

1. (adverb)(idiomatic) "No holds barred"
Describing the engagement in an activity as being without restraint; denoting enthusiastic participation.

EX: "Last night we went '''all-out'''." i.e. We drank a lot/stayed up late/did something to the extreme.

"She went '''all-out''' on that costume."  i.e. Her costume was elaborate- no expense spared.

''Usage:''  Generally used after all forms of the verb "to go."  Acceptable after "to be."